R Notebook

In this project, we are going to predict the churn customer of telecom sector and find out the key drivers that lead to churn. We are going to show how the logistic regression model using R can be used to identify the customer churn in telecome dataset.

Customer churn refers to a decision made by the customer about ending the business relationship. It is also referred to the loss of clients or customers. Customer loyalty and customer churn always add up to 100%. If a firm has a 60% loyalty rate, then their loss or churn rate of customers is 40%. As per 80/20 customer profitability rule, 20% of customers are generating 80% of revenue. So, it is very important to predict the users likely to churn from the business relationship and the factors affecting the customer decisions. Here we are going to show how logistic regression model using R can be used to identify the customer churn in the telecom dataset.

In this project we will seek answers for the following questions: 1. How to identify who is likely to churn 2. What are the factors responsible for churn? 3. Who are most valuable customers 4. How valid is the churn prediction model?

# Random Forest, search=random
#install.packages("randomForest")
library(randomForest)
control <- caret::trainControl(method = 'repeatedcv',
                        number = 10,
                        repeats = 3,
                        search = 'random')
seed <- 1234
metric <- 'Accuracy'
set.seed(seed)
mtry <- sqrt(ncol(train_df))
fit_rf_random <- caret::train(churn~., 
                              data = train_df[1:500,],
                              method = 'rf',
                              metric=metric,
                              tuneLength=15,
                              trControl = control)

Answers

  1. How to identify who is likely to churn? >We test different classifiers, including ensemble methods, to find the model that highest accuracy, as well as high Kappa value. The Kappa statistic (or value) is a metric that compares an Observed Accuracy with an Expected Accuracy (random chance). It is always less than or equal to 1. A value of 1 implies perfect agreement and values less than 1 imply less than perfect agreement.

  2. What are the factors responsible for churn? >Using C5.0 classifiers, the 20 most important variables are: total_day_charge 100.00 total_night_minutes 100.00 total_eve_charge 100.00 number_customer_service_calls 100.00 international_planyes 100.00 total_day_minutes 100.00 stateNJ 100.00 total_intl_minutes 99.58 voice_mail_planyes 99.01 account_length 96.46 total_intl_calls 96.22 total_night_calls 89.71 stateMT 78.31 stateUT 70.60 stateOR 66.67 stateNE 65.83 stateOH 61.84 stateWV 53.62 total_eve_minutes 52.60 stateME 51.61

  3. Who are most valuable customers >The most valuables customers are the ones who generate most revenues to the company in the form of charging (total of day, evening, night and international charges) and showing loyalty through high numbers of account length.

  4. How valid is the churn prediction model? >The churn prediction model using Boosted C5.0 classifiers has accuracy of 0.9598 and Kappa value of 0.8120 (very good agreement).
